<section class="card" aria-label="About this seed starting planner">
  <div class="muted">
    <p>
      Seed starting is mostly a timing problem. Start too early and you end up with tall, stressed seedlings that need weeks of extra care indoors.
      Start too late and warm-season crops may not have enough time to size up before fall. This planner is a simple way to pick dates you can
      actually act on — based on one anchor: your <strong>average last frost date</strong>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Here’s what the planner does with that date: it works backward to give you an indoor sowing window, then places a hardening-off window before
      your outdoor move. The ranges are intentional. Real springs swing from year to year, and “last frost” is a probability, not a promise.
      Think of the early end of a range as “possible in a mild spring (or with protection)” and the late end as “safer when spring drags on.”
    </p>

    <p>
      A common point of confusion is mixing up <em>calendar time</em> with <em>garden readiness</em>. Frost risk is one piece; soil temperature,
      nighttime lows, wind, and sun exposure matter too. If your garden runs colder than your weather app (low spots, open wind, heavy clay, lots of
      shade), your best results usually come from using the later end of the outdoor window — even if the date looks “late on paper.”
      If you’re growing in raised beds, against a warm wall, or under cover, you can often lean earlier, but still watch overnight temps.
    </p>

    <p>
      Use this as a planning baseline, then adjust with local reality. When in doubt: protect tender plants, avoid rushing heat-lovers, and treat
      steady nighttime temperatures as the real “go” signal. The goal is not perfect prediction — it’s a calm, repeatable schedule that keeps your
      seedlings healthy and your season moving.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

