    </li>

    <li>
      Choose a crop. The planner loads typical indoor start times and outdoor timing for that crop (based on common short-season approaches).
    </li>

    <li>
      Pick a <strong>season protection</strong> level only if you truly use it (row cover, cloche, low tunnel).
      Protection can reduce light-frost risk and wind stress, but it doesn’t instantly warm cold soil.
    </li>

    <li>
      Click <strong>Calculate</strong>. You’ll get three practical windows:
      <strong>Start indoors</strong> → <strong>Harden off</strong> → <strong>Transplant / direct sow</strong>.
      Aim for the middle of each range unless you have a clear reason to go earlier or later.
    </li>

    <li>
      Adjust for your microclimate. If your yard runs cold, windy, or shaded, use the later end of the outdoor range.
      If you’re in raised beds or a sheltered spot, you can often lean earlier — but still watch nighttime lows.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <p class="small muted" style="margin-top:10px;">
